‘⁴ ln this passage, Bacon seems explicitly to recognise what we call the Plurality of Causes, namely, the lact that an event may be due to various causes or distinct sets of conditions. An argument might hence be deduced in favour of the position that by Form he invariably intends to express nature or essence rather than cause. As l have stated, however, in the Introduc- tion, 1 believe that the word is employed by him in various shades of meaning in different places. Should it be said that the form is the set of conditions immediately preceding the phenomenon, as it appears to us, and that this is bivariably the same, it must be borne in mind that, even ir we granted this to be the case, the difficulty connected with Plurality of Causes would recur with regard to the set of conditions immediately preceding this, or the set immediately preceding that, and so on ; so that it would only be postponed, not eliminated.
